Skywave — live DSC monitor
==========================

A browser-native decoder for the routine maritime radio traffic almost
nobody reads anymore. Skywave picks dozens of public KiwiSDRs around the
world, tunes each to one of the six international Digital Selective
Calling channels (MF 2187.5 kHz and five HF frequencies), decodes every
burst in JavaScript, deduplicates across receivers, and prints the
result as a scrolling table of who's calling whom, from where, about
what.

One HTML file, five little JS modules, one CSS file, no build step.


Using it
--------
Open the page. It picks up to ~96 public KiwiSDRs covering the DSC
channels and starts listening. The top-right dropdown narrows the scan
to a region (NW Europe, Mediterranean, US East Coast, etc.) — useful
if you want to concentrate on one body of water instead of the whole
ocean.

The audio stays silent between transmissions. When a DSC FSK burst is
detected on one of the receivers we're listening to, the strongest
signal gets routed to your speakers — so you hear the actual tones of
the protocol the first time it happens, which is the fun bit.

Click a row to expand: decoder internals, the full list of receivers
that heard the call, and a mini map of where those receivers sit along
with the vessel's last known position.

Vessel enrichment uses Global Fishing Watch's public search + tracks
endpoints, proxied through the Cloudflare Worker. Ship name, flag,
type, callsign, IMO and a decimated 14-day AIS track come back
automatically for every MMSI that GFW has data on. No API key needed.


Etiquette
---------
Public KiwiSDR receivers have a limited number of user slots. Skywave
only joins a receiver that has at least two free slots at the time of
connection, and drops out automatically if a receiver subsequently
fills up. There is always one slot available for another human
listener. Please don't run Skywave 24/7 in a background tab for
weeks on end — occupying a slot for an hour or two at a time is normal,
occupying it forever is not.


File layout
-----------
index.html    entry point; Leaflet + JetBrains Mono + the app
styles.css    the whole stylesheet, mobile-first
app.js        orchestration: rack, audio routing, call dedupe, CSV
dsc.js        ITU-R M.493 decoder
kiwi.js       KiwiSDR WebSocket audio client
vessels.js    GFW vessel identity lookup
regions.js    DSC channels, regional presets, MID→ISO, geographic helpers
map.js        per-card mini map (Leaflet)
favicon.svg   Data Desk mark
worker/       Cloudflare Worker gateway (WSS→WS tunnel for HTTPS pages)


Local development
-----------------
ES modules need an HTTP server; file:// won't work:

    python3 -m http.server 8000

Then open http://localhost:8000/ — from http:// origins Skywave talks
to KiwiSDRs directly. From https:// origins it tunnels through the
Cloudflare Worker in worker/.

Add ?debug=1 to the URL for verbose console logging of the decoder and
the GFW lookups.


Credits & research
------------------
Decoder ported from the Data Desk research repo at
~/Research/dsc-triangulation. Original Python reference:
scripts/dsc_decode_ddesk.py. Canonical .NET reference:
vendor/TAOSW.DSC_Decoder.Core/GMDSSDecoder.cs.
